<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Letter Book Copy: letters copied into a bound letter-book ]">LB</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Virginia Historical Society, Richmond ]">ViHi</span>: Dinwiddie Papers.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0173-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0173-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>Dinwiddies letter is a point-by-point response to GWs letter of 21 June.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0173-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0173-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>In 1756 the leaders of the Overhill Cherokee town of Tellico carried on secret negotiations with the French, attempting to persuade them to build a fort near their town. Tellico had for years chafed at the supremacy of Chota, the principal city of the upper, or Overhill, Cherokee. Tellico, or Great Tellico, was on the Tellico River west of Chota and the Little Tennessee River.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-04-02-0173-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-02-04-02-0173-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-04-02-0172" class="document">GW to Dinwiddie, this date, n.3</a>.</p>

</div>
